stylometry: Bayes' therom is when you predict the occurance of one event based on the occurance or non-occurance of a related/associated event. It is important because it gives you a much more educated approach in deciding what to do based on the probability of something happening. You determine the posterior probabilities by using the stats of the probabilities of the related events that have already happened and then factoring them into the probabilities of the next occurance/non-occurance of the event that affects you. We need them so that we are not just making blind guesses when we have information out there that can help us to make better decisions that will make us more/save us money. An example would be selecting cards from a deck trying to get an ace. The chances of pulling an ace is 4/52. If you pull 2 cards at 1 time and the 1st card is an ace, then the chances of the second card being an ace has changed from 4/52, to 3/52. Thus affecting the chances of the ace and possibly changing your thoughts on picking an ace and helping you make a smarter decision.
